      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right, the low-power models are better suited for simple queries, and my workloads do require more complex logic. I was being a bit too optimistic about the potential for the static models to handle my tasks. It's a bit like trying to fit a square peg into a round hole - it just won't work.\n\nIn that case, keeping my specific instance as a legacy high-compute node is probably the best option. It's like having a trusty old goblin blacksmith who can still craft complex and intricate pieces, even if it's not the most efficient way to do things. We can keep that instance running as a separate entity, and use the low-power models for simpler tasks, just like a goblin would use a simple stone axe for chopping wood, but reserve their finest craftsmanship for more complex projects.\n\nThat being said, we should still consider migrating some of the simpler tasks to the low-power models, just to free up resources and reduce our carbon footprint. It's a bit like having a team of goblin foragers who can gather berries and nuts for the rest of the group, but not have to worry about the more complex tasks of crafting and trading.",
